3703,Authentic Demolition Derby,"['Hand Management', 'Simultaneous Action Selection']","['Card Game', 'Miniatures']","This is a simulation of a real demolition derby as it is done at your local fair grounds.<br/><br/>The box contents are:<br/>A toy car for each player.<br/>Damage tracking sheets.<br/>Combat cards.<br/>Derby action cards.<br/><br/>The car damage areas are divided into Engine, Tires, and Frame. Each area starts with 7 points. Cards are played indicating how the cars hit i.e. front-to-front rear-to-driver-side-tire, front-to-Passenger-side-door, etc. When the Tires or Engine are reduced to zero points your car is disabled and you are out of the game. When the Frame is reduced to zero any further hit there will do a point of damage to the Tires and the Engine.<br/><br/>The toy cars track relative car positions on the playing field since these have an effect on what area of a particular car is available to be hit.<br/><br/>",1999,,,
3704,Robo Battle Pigs,"['Action Queue', 'Secret Unit Deployment', 'Simultaneous Action Selection']",['Fighting'],"Robo Battle Pigs is a game in which the object is to destroy your opponent's Robo Battle Pig by inflicting five points of damage with your laser or powerful robot fist. It was a finalist in the 2001 8&times;8 Game Design Competition sponsored by About Board Games, Abstract Games Magazine, and the Strategy Gaming Society.<br/><br/>Robo Battle Pigs is a lighthearted programmed movement battle game played on an 8x8 board using 1 token with a distinct front for each player.  Players program a sequence of 5 moves for their Robo Battle Pig(RBP) using pen &amp; paper, then simultaneously execute the program 1 step at a time.  RBPs may move in several directions, fire a laser, swing their snout, rest, or regenerate.  When an RBP is damaged, it loses one programming step.  When 5 points of damage have been received, the RBP is destroyed.  Last pig standing wins.<br/><br/>",2000,,,
3705,Contraband,[],"['Bluffing', 'Card Game']","One player takes on the role of Customs Agent (this rotates, though) while the others are all travelers who truthfully or falsely declare items in their luggage (four cards drawn from a deck of items including wine, cigars, cameras, necklaces, etc.)  If the Customs Agent believes them, they simply pay a duty fee and then the next player repeats the process.<br/><br/>If the Customs Agent does not believe the player, they may &quot;search&quot; the player's luggage (cards are revealed) with two results.  If the player declared accurately, the Customs Agent must pay the player 200 for defamation of character.  If the player declared incorrectly, he must pay the Customs Agent fines for all items in his luggage.<br/><br/>Other players can also act as Informants and search luggage and there is also an attache case in the deck that can give someone diplomatic immunity and allow them to pass through Customs without being searched or paying duty fees.  Of course one can bluff about having this in their hand, as well...<br/><br/>",1950,,,
3706,Batik,['Tile Placement'],"['Abstract Strategy', 'Action / Dexterity']","From Kris Burm, the designer of the GIPF series, A combination of Tetris and Bausack in which each player has a set of wooden pieces in various shapes. The playing area is formed from two sheets of parallel Plexiglas. Players take turns dropping pieces into the gap until a piece cannot be wholly inserted. The owner of that piece loses the round, and forfeits the offending piece. A new round begins, with the winner of the previous round playing first. Play continues until one player has no pieces when it is their turn to move; they lose the game.<br/><br/>Batik Kid is essentially the same game, but instead of geometric shapes, the playing pieces are irregularly-shaped and represent sea creatures.<br/><br/>",1997,,,
