4404,Gold!,"['Commodity Speculation', 'Roll / Spin and Move', 'Stock Holding', 'Trading']",['Economic'],"Using the basic rules, the players start with $1,000,000 and 12 certificates representing financial instruments worth either 900,000, 1,000,000, or 1,100,000 and denominated in either dollars, pounds sterling, deutschemarks, yen, or swiss francs. They proceed around the board, encountering spaces that cause yields to change; prices to change; players to draw Risk or Option cards or roll on the Fate table; players to buy, sell, or swap investments; etc. The first player to reach the &quot;Gold!&quot; space gets an extra $1,000,000 and the game ends immediately; the wealthiest player at that point is the winner.<br/><br/>The advanced rules add fluctuating certificate values and bank auctions of certificates. Playing time is a guess.<br/><br/>The photo on the game cover is of an actual pile of a million pounds sterling worth of gold bullion.<br/><br/>",1981,,,
4405,The Big Deal,"['Betting and Bluffing', 'Roll / Spin and Move', 'Stock Holding']",['Economic'],"A game of quickly changing fortunes, where you try to climb the ladder of success by buying into wacky business opportunities (Rent-A-Monster, Kangaroo Airlines, Paint-On Socks, etc.) and hopefully selling them for a fortune.  (How little things have changed since...)<br/><br/>Your net worth is kept track of using a slide rule of sorts, dubbed the &quot;ladder of success&quot;.  The first player to move into the Ritz by buying or winning steps on his ladder wins.  You can buy into up to four opportunities at once; when you land on another player's opportunity, you can attempt to &quot;bail him out&quot; of it by paying the bail out price and beating him on the dice.<br/><br/>The &quot;Chance of a Lifetime&quot; circle is entered on doubles or by landing on an entry space; if you enter it, you may roll as often as you wish, hoping to land on the Big Deal space (which gives you 3 ladder steps) or another good space (where you sell your opportunities for varying profit).  Of course, the circle also includes bad spaces, so there is considerable risk...<br/><br/>A few other spaces round out the board, giving you the opportunity to challenge other players (swapping a ladder step) and other things like that.<br/><br/>The game is sort of a cross between Can't Stop and Monopoly.<br/><br/>",1977,,,
4406,Archimedes,[],['Abstract Strategy'],"This travel-sized version of the four-player Archimedes Professional is played on a 7x6 board.  The object is to capture the opponent's King by surrounding him with colored pegs.  The Kings are the black and white pegs and start on the Throne squares at either end of the board.  The other 30 pegs are multi-colored.<br/><br/>On your move, you first move your King defensively, by sliding to an adjacent free space.  Next, you place a colored peg offensively, hoping to box the opponent King in.<br/><br/>An optional rule allows a captured King to displace a colored peg if it happens to lie on a straight line away from him along with another same-color peg (at any distance).  Further, Kings aren't allowed to come adjacent to each other.<br/><br/>",1983,,,
