4476,Electronic Talking Hot Potato,[],"['Action / Dexterity', ""Children's Game"", 'Party Game', 'Real-time']","A high-pressure game of getting rid of a &quot;hot&quot; potato so as not to be holding it when time runs out.<br/><br/>This game probably goes way back. Sidney Addy's Glossary of Sheffield Words describes a game in which &quot;a number of people sit in a row, or in chairs round a parlor. A lighted taper is handed to the first, who says:<br/><br/>Jack's alive, and likely to live<br/>If he dies in your hand, you've a forfeit to give.<br/><br/>The one in whose hand the light expires has to pay the forfeit.&quot;<br/><br/>That was written in 1888.<br/><br/>Apparently later it was played with an actual hot potato. Whoever ended up with the potato when the music stopped was kicked out and the potato elimination match continued.<br/><br/>By the 1950s, manufactured Hot Potato games were already on store shelves. Remco&rsquo;s late 1950s version used small plastic pans for each player, covered up so that no one would know who was holding the real potato. In the 1960s, there was &ldquo;Spudsie,&rdquo; a wind-up potato who emitted a loud DING when time was up. In the 1980s, there was the battery-powered &ldquo;Chip O&rsquo;Grattin.&rdquo; Most recently there is a battery-powered talking potato, which shouts out &ldquo;Yahoo!&rdquo;<br/><br/>",1988,,,
