4900,Richie Rich,['Roll / Spin and Move'],"[""Children's Game"", 'Movies / TV / Radio theme']","Richie Rich is based on the comics of the same name.  In this board game, players assume the roles of the titular character and his friends.  Their objective is to deposit jewels at the bank and return home.  Standing in their way are thieves and the pranks of Richie's cousin, Reggie.<br/><br/>Players move their pieces along the track by rolling a die.  They may move forwards or backwards.  When they land on a space, they must follow the instructions on it: for example, Reggie makes players lose a turn, while short-cut spaces let players move their pieces further ahead.  Thief spaces, however, stop a moving piece in its tracks and hold it there.  Players must draw an Invention card each turn to obtain one with a number that matches the thief's to escape the criminal's space and continue moving.<br/><br/>The first player to land exactly on the Finish spot wins and ends the game.<br/><br/>",1982,,,
4901,Inspecteur Gadget,['Roll / Spin and Move'],"[""Children's Game"", 'Movies / TV / Radio theme']","In the Inspector Gadget game (based on the cartoon of the same name), players take on the role of the titular bungling cyborg detective in a quest to capture villains from the MAD (Mean And Dirty) organization.<br/><br/>Players move on the board along a circular track by using the results of a spinner.  Along the track are spaces that move a player piece, stop it, or make the player lose a turn.  There are also villain tokens placed on the board that move around.  Players capture these villains by landing their Inspector Gadget exactly onto the tokens.  Players can also steal a villain token from each other by landing on their opponents.  Lastly, villains can liberate their fellow criminals by moving onto the players' pieces.<br/><br/>The first player to reach the Jail, while holding three or more villains captive, wins the game.<br/><br/>",1983,,,
4902,Antinale al Precio,['Betting and Bluffing'],"['Movies / TV / Radio theme', 'Puzzle', 'Trivia']",Seven different versions of the American version of the game exist but all work the same way: One player acts as host to set up the puzzles and verify correct answers. The other players make bids on prizes. The player who bids closest without going over plays a pricing game against the house for more prizes. (The television series rotates over seventy different games. Some home game editions contains as many as forty-five games; some as few as six.)<br/><br/>The finale is called the Showcase Round. The two players involved may be the players with the highest scores or it may be the players who won their respective Showcase Showdowns. (It depends on the edition of the game.) Each player has three prizes. Each guesses what the total value of one's own three prizes is. The person who guesses closer without going over is the winner.<br/><br/>Foreign language versions have been adapted with respect to their countries and currencies.<br/><br/>,1973,,,
